Reasoning: The paper discusses the performance of Skip-Gram with Negative Sampling, a popular algorithm in natural language processing, in capturing second-order co-occurrence information. This topic falls under the sub-category of computational linguistics (cs.CL). The paper also compares the algorithm to Singular Value Decomposition, which is a technique commonly used in machine learning (cs.LG). Additionally, the paper discusses the impact of additional information on the models, which relates to information retrieval (cs.IR) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Finally, the empirical study conducted in the paper involves analyzing the models' reactions, which falls under the sub-category of social and information networks (cs.SI).
